  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"aphelios","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Aphelios"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"With all three abilities you dominate: Double Up (Q) bounces off the lane minion into Aphelios for a chunk, then Strut (E passive) lets you kite off after Make It Rain (E) slows him. Aphelios has no dash and only one weapon pair up at a time, so every time he steps to CS you get a free Q-auto trade he can't answer."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time flips any even standoff — Aphelios is immobile and squishy, so if your support lands a root or you catch him near a wave, the channel deletes him. Look to force it whenever he's shoved under and has to walk up to last-hit, and hold it as an all-in deterrent once he has Gravitum for a self-peel root."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike (Kraken/Galeforce or Noonquiver into IE path) lands before Aphelios comes fully online, since his kit only scales once he stacks weapons and items. Keep hard-shoving and forcing him to give up CS or eat Q pokes so he falls behind the curve where his DPS ceiling lives."},{"when":"Late","text":"This is Aphelios's window — with full weapons, Infernum/Crescendum cleave and Moonlight ult ranges, he out-DPSes you in a straight extended fight. In teamfights don't stand and duel; use Bullet Time from an angle he isn't holding, then Strut-kite while your frontline denies him free positioning."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade with Q bounce whenever he walks up to CS with a weak weapon pair","Punish his lack of a dash with support CC all-ins","End the game before his full-weapon late-game scaling arrives"],"foe":["Reach 3+ items with the right weapon rotation online","Get Gravitum or a support root to lock you out of Strut-kiting","Drag the game to a stand-and-DPS teamfight where his cleave wins"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 favour you: Double Up out-ranges his auto-poke and bounces for bonus damage, and Aphelios has no early kill pressure without a dash. Contest the first waves and chip him whenever he steps up to last-hit.","mid":"Levels 3-6 are your strongest stretch. Make It Rain slows him for a guaranteed Q-auto trade, Strut lets you disengage before he can retaliate, and at 6 Bullet Time punishes his immobility hard. Keep the wave shoved to force him under tower where your poke stacks up.","late":"By full items Aphelios pulls ahead — his weapon cleave and range out-sustain your DPS in extended duels. Stop trying to 1v1; ult from an unheld angle, kite with Strut, and let your team peel while you deal burst from max range.","whys":["Level 1 is yours because Double Up out-ranges and out-damages his single-weapon auto poke.","Level 2 stays yours as Make It Rain zones his walk-ups while he still lacks any escape.","Level 3 favours you with the full Q-E-kite combo online against an immobile lane bully.","Levels 4-5 are yours since your poke compounds and he can't punish back without a dash.","Level 6 is yours because Bullet Time hard-punishes his zero-mobility, squishy frame.","First item is yours as your crit spike arrives before his weapon-stacking scaling.","2+ items flips to Aphelios once full weapons and cleave out-DPS you in extended fights."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"ashe","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Ashe"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You win every short trade: Double Up bounces off a minion into Ashe for burst, and Make It Rain both slows her and denies her the frost-passive kiting she relies on. Ashe has no dash, so once you E her she can't peel your follow-up autos, and Strut refunds your movement to stay on top of her."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time massively out-ranges and out-bursts a stationary Volley trade — if she Volleys and you angle the ult from behind minions, you win the exchange outright. Her only equalizer is Enchanted Crystal Arrow: respect a saved R as all-in setup, but if she blows it to disengage you get a free window to shove and poke."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your crit/lethality first item spikes your Q burst hard, while Ashe's power is DPS that needs uptime she can't get when you're slowing and bursting her. Keep shoving to deny her free CS and punish every walk-up, staying ahead of her item timings."},{"when":"Late","text":"Ashe's utility and DPS scale past you in the 5v5 — Ranger's Focus DPS plus perma-slow and a game-changing R make her the safer carry in a spread fight. Don't duel her at max stacks; use your ult on grouped enemies from an angle, and let your frontline body-block her arrow while you output from the back."}],"wants":{"you":["Land Make It Rain to strip her frost-passive kiting and slow her for Q trades","Trade in short bursts where your Double Up out-damages her Volley poke","Punish any Enchanted Crystal Arrow she spends on disengage"],"foe":["Free-farm to her DPS item spikes with Ranger's Focus uptime","Land a long-range R engage to set up an all-in on you","Reach a spread teamfight where her utility and perma-slow shine"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are yours: Double Up out-ranges Volley in a straight poke war and bounces for extra damage, and Ashe can't punish your steps because she has no mobility. Contest CS and chip her each time she walks up.","mid":"Levels 3-6 you hold a clear edge. Make It Rain slows her and shuts off her frost kiting, letting your Q-auto trades win outright, and at 6 Bullet Time out-bursts any Volley standoff. Keep the wave moving into her so she farms under tower and eats poke.","late":"Ashe pulls ahead by full items — Ranger's Focus DPS, perma-slow, and R utility make her the stronger teamfighter. Stop dueling; place your ult on the grouped enemy line, kite with Strut, and rely on peel so her arrow doesn't catch you out.","whys":["Level 1 is yours as Double Up out-ranges and out-trades her Volley poke.","Level 2 stays yours because Make It Rain zones her while she has no escape.","Level 3 favours you with the slow-plus-burst combo against an immobile lane.","Levels 4-5 are yours as your trade pattern compounds a CS and health lead.","Level 6 is yours since Bullet Time out-bursts a stationary Volley exchange.","First item is yours as your crit Q spike lands ahead of her DPS uptime needs.","2+ items flips to Ashe once her DPS, perma-slow, and R utility scale past you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"caitlyn","win":["Caitlyn","Caitlyn","Caitlyn","Caitlyn","Skill","Skill","Caitlyn"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Caitlyn owns this range war: her 650 auto range and Piltover Peacemaker (Q) out-poke your Double Up, and she traps you against the wave to force headshot procs. Respect her Yordle Snap Trap (W) placements in the bushes and on the retreat path — stepping on one gives her a guaranteed empowered auto burst. Only trade when her Q is down and you can bounce Double Up off a low minion, then Strut away before she resets range."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"This is your best window — Bullet Time out-damages her level-6 pattern because her R (Ace in the Hole) is a single-target execute, not a lane-fight tool. If she oversteps to trap or headshot you, a support slow into your ult channel can flip the exchange. Even here she'd rather poke from max range than commit, so ping and punish any greedy walk-up."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Skill window: your first-item crit spike closes some of the gap, but Caitlyn's own Noonquiver/IE timing keeps her poke lethal. Whoever plays the trap-and-range dance better wins — you look to burst her when she's caught out of position, she looks to chunk you at 650 range and cage you against a trap."},{"when":"Late","text":"Caitlyn falls off relative to hypercarries but still beats you in lane-scaling teamfights via range and trap zoning, and her long-range R sniping picks. Don't try to walk her down; use Bullet Time from an angle she can't peacemaker, kite with Strut, and let your team collapse before she cages you."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade only when her Peacemaker Q is on cooldown","Land a support slow into Bullet Time when she oversteps","Burst her the moment she's caught out of position"],"foe":["Poke you freely from her superior 650 auto range","Cage you against a wave or Yordle Snap Trap for a headshot","Keep the lane at max range so you can never trade even"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 favour Caitlyn: her range and Piltover Peacemaker out-poke your Double Up, and her traps deny you safe walk-ups. Focus on safe CS, dodge Q, and never last-hit standing on a trap.","mid":"Levels 3-5 stay Caitlyn's — she zones you off the wave and forces headshot procs by pinning you against minions. Only step up when her Q is down, bounce Double Up for chip, then Strut off before she re-establishes range.","late":"Around level 6 to first item it's a skill matchup: Bullet Time and your crit spike let you punish her overextensions, but she caps back with trap zoning and R picks. By full items her range advantage in teamfights returns the edge to Caitlyn, so ult from unheld angles and rely on peel.","whys":["Level 1 is Caitlyn's because her auto range and Q out-poke your Double Up.","Level 2 stays Caitlyn's as her trap placements deny your walk-ups.","Level 3 favours Caitlyn since she cages you against the wave for headshots.","Levels 4-5 are Caitlyn's with range zoning keeping you off farm.","Level 6 is a skill window as Bullet Time out-damages her single-target R pattern.","First item is even — your crit spike trades against her lethal Q poke timing.","2+ items returns to Caitlyn via superior teamfight range and R picks."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"corki","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Corki"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You out-trade an early Corki hard: Double Up bounces off a minion for burst while his Phosphorus Bomb (Q) and Gatling Gun (E) are short-ranged and mana-hungry pre-items. Make It Rain slows him so he can't kite your follow-up autos, and Strut keeps you on him. Corki is squishy and immobile aside from Valkyrie (W), so punish every walk-up before his package spikes online."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time out-bursts his level-6 lane pattern — Corki's power at 6 is map presence via the Special Delivery package, not a lane-fight R. If he Valkyries in to trade, slow him with E and channel the ult; he has to burn W to escape and then he's stranded. Force him to farm defensively while you shove and poke."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Skill window: Corki's first Trinity/tri-force-adjacent item plus stacked Hextech Munitions makes his mixed-damage DPS and true-damage passive scary, but your crit Q spike still bursts him if he mispositions. Whoever hits their item first and lands their key ability — your Q bounce vs his Bomb-into-Gatling — wins the exchange."},{"when":"Late","text":"Corki pulls ahead by two-plus items: his mixed magic/physical damage and true-damage passive shred through armor stacking, out-DPSing you in extended fights. Don't stand and duel; use Bullet Time from an angle outside his Gatling cone, kite with Strut, and let your team pressure before his package flanks land."}],"wants":{"you":["Trade early while his Q/E are mana-hungry and short-ranged","Slow him with Make It Rain so he can't Gatling-kite your autos","Punish walk-ups before his first-item mixed-damage spike"],"foe":["Reach his first big item with Hextech Munitions online","Use the Special Delivery package for map pressure and flanks","Drag fights long where his true-damage DPS shreds your armor"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are yours: Double Up out-ranges and out-damages Corki's short poke while he's mana-starved. Contest CS and chip him whenever he steps up to farm.","mid":"Levels 3-5 stay firmly yours. Make It Rain slows him out of Gatling-kite range, your Q bounce burst wins trades, and at 6 Bullet Time out-damages his lane pattern since his R is a roam tool. Keep the wave shoved to deny his defensive farm.","late":"Level 6 to first item is skill — you punish mispositions but his Hextech mixed damage catches up. By two items Corki's true-damage DPS shreds you in extended fights, so stop dueling, ult from outside his Gatling cone, and rely on Strut kiting and team peel.","whys":["Level 1 is yours as Double Up out-ranges his mana-hungry short poke.","Level 2 stays yours because Make It Rain zones his squishy walk-ups.","Level 3 favours you with the slow-plus-burst combo out-trading his kit.","Levels 4-5 are yours as your poke compounds before his items arrive.","Level 6 is yours since Bullet Time out-bursts his roam-oriented R pattern.","First item is a skill window — your crit spike trades against his Hextech mixed damage.","2+ items flips to Corki as his true-damage DPS shreds you in long fights."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"draven","win":["Draven","Draven","Draven","Draven","Draven","Draven","Draven"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Draven's Spinning Axes (Q) give him a massive early auto-damage lead — every catch means a two-to-three-hundred bonus-damage auto that shreds you before your Double Up bounce even lands. Stand Aside (E) cancels your Make It Rain approach and knocks you off, and Blood Rush (W) lets him close and kite better than your Strut. Don't try to straight-up trade; only chip Q from max range when he's forced to move for an axe."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time does not out-trade Draven's snowball at 6 — his lane damage plus Whirling Death (R) global gives him kill pressure you can't match. If he has axes stacked and W up, he'll walk you down through your ult. Play for support CC and only channel Bullet Time if he's already CC'd, otherwise you'll get run down mid-cast."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Draven's bounty economy means his first item often comes early and swollen from Adoration gold, spiking his auto DPS even further ahead of yours. Your crit spike helps but rarely closes the gap in a straight duel — deny his axe catches by forcing him to choose between chasing an axe and trading, and never fight when both axes are up."},{"when":"Late","text":"Even late Draven out-DPSes you in a bruiser-carry duel with axes and W kiting, though he falls off if he stops snowballing. In teamfights don't face-check him; use Bullet Time from a flank he can't reach, kite with Strut behind your frontline, and rely on peel — a caught Draven who drops his axes is where your burst finally matters."}],"wants":{"you":["Chip Q from max range only when he moves to catch an axe","Save Make It Rain and support CC to punish his axe-chasing","Fight only when both his Spinning Axes are on the ground"],"foe":["Catch axes for repeated 200+ bonus-damage autos","Land Stand Aside to cancel your approach and knock you off","Snowball the Adoration bounty into an early swollen first item"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are Draven's: his Spinning Axes out-damage your Double Up in any straight trade and he can all-in the moment you step up. Play safe, dodge his axe-catch lunges, and farm from max range.","mid":"Levels 3-6 stay Draven's — Blood Rush kites your Strut, Stand Aside cancels your Make It Rain, and his snowball damage means even Bullet Time won't win a fair fight. Only trade Q pokes when he's committed to catching an axe, and lean on your support's CC.","late":"Draven keeps the edge through items via axe DPS and W kiting, only falling off if he's denied snowball. Never duel him; ult from an unheld flank, Strut-kite behind your team, and let peel force him to drop his axes before you burst.","whys":["Level 1 is Draven's because Spinning Axes out-damage your Double Up trade.","Level 2 stays Draven's as he can all-in with axes the moment you step up.","Level 3 favours Draven with Blood Rush kiting and Stand Aside canceling you.","Levels 4-5 are Draven's as his snowballing auto damage outpaces your poke.","Level 6 is Draven's since his lane pressure plus R beats a fair Bullet Time.","First item is Draven's as Adoration bounty spikes his DPS ahead of yours.","2+ items stays Draven's — axe DPS and W kiting out-duel you all game."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"ezreal","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You out-trade Ezreal in raw lane damage: Double Up bounces off a minion for burst that beats a single Mystic Shot (Q), and if he steps up to poke you punish with Q-auto plus Make It Rain slow. Ezreal's only safety is Arcane Shift (E), so bait it — once his E is down he's immobile and squishy, and Strut keeps you in range to chunk him. Deny his Q by standing so it can't hit both you and a minion for the mana refund."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time out-bursts his lane pattern since Trueshot Barrage is a poke ult, not a fight-winner — if his E is on cooldown and your support has a slow or root, your channel kills him. Force him to use E defensively, then all-in the window. He'd rather sit back and poke, so ping every time his Arcane Shift is down."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Skill window: Ezreal's Trinity/Manamune first-item spike is real and his Q poke starts stacking chunk from a safe range, but your crit Double Up still bursts him if he mispositions or wastes E. Whoever plays the E-cooldown dance better wins — you punish him E-down, he pokes you from max range with it up."},{"when":"Late","text":"You keep a slight edge into the late game because Ezreal is a poke-and-kite carry with no reliable burst on you, while your Bullet Time and crit Q output real teamfight damage. Use your ult on the grouped enemy from an angle, Strut-kite his skillshots, and force fights before he can whittle your team with safe Q poke."}],"wants":{"you":["Bait Arcane Shift, then all-in while his E is on cooldown","Bounce Double Up off a minion to out-burst his Mystic Shot","Land Make It Rain to slow him for a Q-auto trade"],"foe":["Poke safely from max range with Mystic Shot and E up","Hit his Manamune/Trinity first-item spike to stack chunk damage","Kite fights with E so you can never commit an all-in"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are yours: Double Up out-damages a single Mystic Shot and bounces for burst, and Ezreal can't punish back without spending Arcane Shift. Contest CS and chip him whenever he walks up.","mid":"Levels 3-6 stay yours. Make It Rain slows him for guaranteed Q-auto trades, and every time you bait his E you get a free all-in window. At 6 Bullet Time out-bursts his poke ult, so shove him in and punish any E-down step.","late":"Around first item it's skill — his Manamune poke spike trades against your crit burst. But by two items you edge back ahead, since Ezreal lacks burst on you while your ult and Q deal real fight damage; ult grouped enemies from an angle and kite his skillshots.","whys":["Level 1 is yours as Double Up out-damages a single Mystic Shot poke.","Level 2 stays yours because Make It Rain zones his walk-ups.","Level 3 favours you with the slow-plus-burst combo forcing his E out.","Levels 4-5 are yours as baiting Arcane Shift hands you free all-in windows.","Level 6 is yours since Bullet Time out-bursts his poke-only Trueshot ult.","First item is a skill window — his Manamune poke trades against your crit burst.","2+ items returns to you as your fight damage beats his no-burst poke kit."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"heimerdinger","win":["Heimerdinger","Heimerdinger","Heimerdinger","Heimerdinger","Heimerdinger","Heimerdinger","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Your Double Up (Q) bounce off the front minion can hit Heimerdinger if he's stacked behind low-HP creeps, but his H-28G Turrets (Q) zone your Love Tap approach so you rarely get a clean auto trade. Punish him only when a turret expires or he's out of position collecting a cannon."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is your only real equalizer, but Heimerdinger's turret wall and CH-2 Electron Grenade (W) stun make it hard to channel safely; wait for his grenade to whiff or hold your ult for a support-CC all-in rather than solo blasting into his turret nest."},{"when":"1st item","text":"His turret DPS still out-zones your first-item wave clear, and a fed Heimer with Liandry's shreds you if you facecheck. Keep farming from max range and let Strut roam you to sidelanes; do not force the 2v2."},{"when":"Late","text":"This is your window: once you have two-plus items and a peeling support, Bullet Time deletes his turret line and both enemies in a single channel from behind your frontline, flipping the lane's early oppression."}],"wants":{"you":["Two completed items so Bullet Time one-shots his turret field and both champions","A support with hard engage or a shield to close his poke gap","Teamfights where you AoE his stacked turrets and squishies from max range"],"foe":["A static 2v2 lane where his turret wall walls off your approach","Landing CH-2 Electron Grenade stuns to zone your Bullet Time channel","Poking you down with turret beams and Hextech Micro-Rockets before you spike"]},"early":"Heimerdinger owns levels 1-2: his H-28G Turrets set up a no-go zone the instant he plants them, so you can't Love Tap trade and last-hitting under his turret pressure costs you CS. Play safe, farm what you can from range, and never facecheck a bush he could have grenaded.","mid":"Levels 3-6 stay his: the turret wall plus CH-2 Electron Grenade stun make any all-in into his nest suicidal, and even your Bullet Time is easy for him to interrupt or wall off. Ping your support to disengage and farm the tempo rather than trading into layered turret DPS.","late":"The lock flips to you at two-plus items. With Bullet Time up and a peel support, you channel from behind your minions and shred his entire turret line and both enemies at once, turning his lane bully phase into your teamfight payoff.","whys":["Heimerdinger's level-1 turret plant creates an instant zone that shuts down your Love Tap trades.","At level 2 his turret plus auto poke out-trades your Double Up before you have kill pressure.","Level 3 gives him the full turret wall and grenade, making the 2v2 his to dictate.","Through levels 4-5 his layered turret DPS keeps zoning you off farm and off engages.","At 6 his grenade stun and turret nest can interrupt or wall your Bullet Time channel.","At one item his turret DPS still out-zones your wave clear and poke.","By two-plus items Bullet Time from range wipes his turret line and both champions, flipping the matchup to you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"jhin","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Miss Fortune","Skill","Jhin"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Both of you are poke-oriented: your Double Up (Q) reset off a dying minion answers his fourth-shot Whisper burst, and Love Tap keeps your auto trades even. Space so he can't land Dancing Grenade (Q) on you off a minion and punish his reload windows when his gun locks him out of attacking."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"This is your spike: Bullet Time out-ranges and out-damages his Curtain Call (R) in a 2v2 because he must stand still to snipe while you can force the fight with a support engage. Blow him up during his reload or bait his ult, then channel from behind minions for the AoE."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Jhin's first-item spike is brutal - Deathfire Grasp-style burst from a critting fourth shot plus his passive AS on kills makes trades a coinflip again, so it's back to skill. Respect his fourth shot and don't stand in Deadly Flourish (W) root range."},{"when":"Late","text":"Jhin pulls ahead: his fourth-shot execute crits and Curtain Call let him poke your team from screen-range before fights start, and if his support roots you his burst deletes you before you can channel Bullet Time."}],"wants":{"you":["Level 6 windows where Bullet Time punishes his stationary Curtain Call","Catching him mid-reload when his gun locks him out of autos","A support engage to force the fight before his fourth shot lines up"],"foe":["Landing Deadly Flourish roots off a support setup to chain his fourth-shot burst","First-item and late-game where his crit fourth shot out-bursts your trades","Free Curtain Call poke on your team from max range before teamfights"]},"early":"Levels 1-4 are a skill matchup: you both want to poke, so it comes down to who lands cleaner. Your Double Up reset and Love Tap keep autos even with his Dancing Grenade and fourth-shot Whisper, but if he catches you off a minion bounce or a Deadly Flourish root the trade swings hard. Farm carefully and don't eat his empowered fourth shot for free.","mid":"Level 6 is your one clear edge: Bullet Time forces the 2v2 on your terms because Jhin's Curtain Call needs him rooted in place to snipe. Punish his reload lockouts and use a support engage to blow him up before his burst lines up.","late":"Jhin reclaims the lock at items: his critting fourth shot and Curtain Call let him whittle your team from screen-range, and a single support root chains into enough burst to kill you before you can channel. Stay behind your frontline and never facecheck his fourth shot.","whys":["Level 1 is even - both of you are pure poke champs trading off minion spacing.","Level 2 stays a skill fight decided by who lands autos and Dancing Grenade cleaner.","At level 3 his fourth-shot burst and your Double Up reset keep trades balanced.","Through levels 4-5 the poke war remains a coinflip on positioning and roots.","At 6 Bullet Time forces the fight on your terms while his Curtain Call needs him stationary.","At one item his crit fourth shot restores the burst parity, making it skill again.","Late, his screen-range fourth-shot execute and Curtain Call poke out-scale your channel."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"jinx","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Jinx"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You out-trade Jinx hard in the early 2v2: your Double Up (Q) and Love Tap burst punish her before she can stack Pow-Pow attack speed, and her Fishbones (rockets) do nothing in melee range so she has no safe way to answer your autos. Walk her down whenever her Flame Chompers (E) are down."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time beats a level-6 Jinx cleanly - she has no mobility and no self-peel besides Chompers, so a support engage into your channel from behind minions kills her before Get Excited resets can save her. This is a prime all-in window."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike still leads: she needs kills or takedowns to snowball Get Excited, and if you keep denying her resets she stays a stationary target for your burst. Keep punishing until she completes her second item."},{"when":"Late","text":"Jinx flips the matchup hard: with two-plus items her rocket range out-zones you, Get Excited resets make her uncatchable in fights, and her DPS eclipses yours. Late teamfights are about avoiding her cleanup, not dueling her."}],"wants":{"you":["Early 2v2 all-ins before she stacks attack speed or gets resets","A support with engage to punish her total lack of mobility","Killing her repeatedly to deny Get Excited snowball"],"foe":["Reaching two-plus items where Fishbones out-ranges your effective damage","Free Get Excited resets that make her untouchable in teamfights","A scaling game where her sustained DPS overtakes your burst"]},"early":"You dominate levels 1-2: Jinx is one of the weakest early laners, and your Double Up plus Love Tap out-trade her before Pow-Pow stacks up. Her rockets are useless up close, so push the auto advantage and last-hit freely while zoning her off CS.","mid":"Levels 3-6 stay yours. Every trade favors you as long as you respect Flame Chompers, and at 6 Bullet Time plus a support engage kills her outright since she has zero mobility. Force all-ins now to build a lead before she scales.","late":"Jinx takes over at two-plus items: her rocket range, Get Excited resets, and raw DPS out-scale everything you do. Stop dueling her - play for picks before fights and use Bullet Time as a peel/zone tool from your backline rather than trying to out-damage her.","whys":["At level 1 your Love Tap and Double Up out-trade Jinx's weak early damage.","Level 2 keeps you ahead - her rockets are useless in the trading range you dictate.","At 3 your burst combo beats her before Pow-Pow attack speed stacks.","Through levels 4-5 she stays immobile and you punish every Chompers cooldown.","At 6 Bullet Time plus engage kills a mobility-less Jinx before resets trigger.","At one item you still lead by denying her the Get Excited snowball.","By two-plus items her rocket range, resets, and DPS flip the matchup fully to her."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"kaisa","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Kai'Sa"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You out-trade an early Kai'Sa easily: your Double Up (Q) and Love Tap burst punish her before she stacks Plasma, and her Icathian Rain (Q) missiles do chip damage but can't win a straight-up 2v2 exchange against your combo. Walk her down when her W (Void Seeker) is on cooldown."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Kai'Sa's level-6 Killer Instinct gives her a dash, but with no target in lane it's just a repositioning tool; your Bullet Time plus a support engage from behind minions still bursts her down before her Evolved Q shreds you. Force the all-in while she's the weaker duelist."},{"when":"1st item","text":"You still lead at one item - she needs two items and an evolve breakpoint before her DPS scales, so keep denying her Plasma stacks and CS to delay that spike. Every kill you take now pushes her power curve back."},{"when":"Late","text":"Kai'Sa takes over hard: evolved Q shreds, evolved W long-range poke, and R repositioning into your backline make her a monster your static kit can't chase. Late fights are about surviving her dive, not dueling her."}],"wants":{"you":["Early all-ins before she reaches item and evolve breakpoints","A support engage to punish her weak early 2v2 damage","Denying Plasma stacks and CS to delay her power spikes"],"foe":["Reaching two items and evolves where her DPS and mobility explode","Using Killer Instinct R to dive your backline in teamfights","Scaling into a mid-late game where her sustained damage out-duels you"]},"early":"You win levels 1-2: Kai'Sa is a weak early laner, and your Love Tap plus Double Up out-trade her before she stacks Plasma or evolves anything. Her Icathian Rain chips but can't answer your burst, so push the auto advantage and zone her off farm.","mid":"Levels 3-6 stay yours. Keep punishing every Void Seeker cooldown and force the 2v2 with a support engage - even her level-6 dash can't save her from Bullet Time when she's the weaker duelist. Build your lead before her evolves come online.","late":"Kai'Sa flips the matchup at two-plus items: evolved Q shred, long-range evolved W, and R repositioning let her dive your backline and out-DPS you outright. Play for picks and use Bullet Time to peel and zone rather than trying to chase her mobility.","whys":["At level 1 your burst combo out-trades Kai'Sa's weak early damage.","Level 2 stays yours - she can't answer Love Tap trades before Plasma stacks.","At 3 your Double Up combo beats her straight-up in the 2v2.","Through levels 4-5 you punish every Void Seeker cooldown while she's still weak.","At 6 Bullet Time plus engage kills her before her dash or evolves matter.","At one item you still lead by delaying her evolve and Plasma breakpoints.","By two-plus items her evolves and R mobility out-scale and out-duel you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"kalista","win":["Kalista","Kalista","Kalista","Kalista","Skill","Skill","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Kalista owns the early 2v2: her Rend (E) stacks off every auto and Pierce (Q) poke, plus Martial Poise hops make her impossible to pin down for your Love Tap trades. She'll whittle you with spear stacks and detonate for a burst you can't answer, so play defensively behind minions."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"This is a skill window: her Fate's Call (R) ult sets up her support's engage, but if you dodge the knock-up and answer with Bullet Time you can equalize the fight. Positioning decides it - don't get caught out of channel range when her support flanks."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Still skill-dependent - her Rend execute and mobility keep her a slippery target, but your first-item Bullet Time gives you real AoE burst in the 2v2 if you can force a static fight. Whoever controls spacing and CC wins the exchange."},{"when":"Late","text":"You pull ahead: Kalista's damage falls off relative to crit ADCs, while your two-plus-item Bullet Time deletes her low-range self in teamfights. Her hops don't save her from an AoE channel behind your frontline, so late fights favor you."}],"wants":{"you":["Late teamfights where two-item Bullet Time out-damages her fall-off","Static fights that punish her short effective range","Dodging Fate's Call so her support engage whiffs"],"foe":["The early laning phase where Rend stacks and hops dominate trades","Landing Fate's Call to launch her support onto you","Kiting you with Martial Poise so you can't land Love Tap autos"]},"early":"Kalista dominates levels 1-4: her Rend stacks off every spear and auto, and Martial Poise hops let her dodge your Double Up and Love Tap while chunking you. Any all-in she can kite until the Rend detonation bursts you, so farm passively behind minions and don't overextend into her spacing.","mid":"Level 6 evens out to skill: her Fate's Call can launch her support onto you, but if you sidestep the engage and answer with Bullet Time you trade back. First item stays a coinflip decided by who controls the spacing and CC in the 2v2.","late":"You take over at two-plus items. Kalista's damage falls off relative to crit-scaling carries, and your Bullet Time deletes her fragile, short-range frame from behind your frontline where her hops can't escape the channel. Group and force AoE fights.","whys":["Kalista's level-1 Rend stacking and Pierce poke out-trade you immediately.","At level 2 her hops dodge your autos while spear stacks chunk you.","Level 3 gives her Rend detonation, bursting you in any trade.","Through levels 4-5 her mobility and stack pressure keep the lane hers.","At 6 it evens out - dodging Fate's Call lets your Bullet Time answer her engage.","At one item spacing and CC decide the fight, keeping it skill.","By two-plus items her fall-off and your AoE burst flip the matchup to you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"karthus","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Bot-lane Karthus is a farm-and-poke oddity: his Lay Waste (Q) needs clean landings and he has no mobility or self-peel, so your Double Up (Q) and Love Tap out-trade him hard in a straight 2v2. Walk him down whenever his Wall of Pain (W) is on cooldown and punish his mana-hungry early game."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"This is the skill window: his Requiem (R) is a global execute that can steal kills or finish you from range, so respect your own HP threshold. Your Bullet Time still forces a stronger direct 2v2, but a low-HP misplay lets his ult punish you, keeping this phase even."},{"when":"1st item","text":"You reclaim the edge - your first-item Bullet Time gives real AoE burst while he's still a squishy, immobile caster with no escape. Force the all-in with a support engage before his Q poke scales and he stays easy to collapse on."},{"when":"Late","text":"You stay ahead in the 2v2 duel: Karthus is defenseless once you're on top of him, and Bullet Time from behind minions bursts him before his Q poke matters. Just respect Requiem's global finish on your team and don't fight at low HP."}],"wants":{"you":["Direct 2v2 all-ins that punish his zero mobility and no self-peel","A support engage to close his Wall of Pain poke gap","First-item Bullet Time windows to burst him before his Q scales"],"foe":["Landing repeated Lay Waste pokes to chunk you from range","Using Requiem to execute you or your support at low HP","Free farm and poke phases where he never has to fight you directly"]},"early":"You beat bot-lane Karthus levels 1-2: he's an immobile caster who wants to farm and poke with Lay Waste, and your Love Tap plus Double Up out-trade him whenever he steps up. Punish his mana-hungry early game and zone him off CS while respecting his Wall of Pain slow.","mid":"Levels 3-5 stay yours, but level 6 evens to skill because Requiem is a global execute - your Bullet Time forces a stronger 2v2, yet fighting at low HP lets his ult punish the misplay. Track your own health and force all-ins when you're healthy.","late":"You keep the edge at items: Karthus has no escape, so first-item and two-item Bullet Time from behind your frontline bursts him down before his poke scales. Duel him freely up close - just never sit at low HP where Requiem can finish you or your support globally.","whys":["At level 1 your burst combo out-trades an immobile, mana-hungry Karthus.","Level 2 stays yours as you punish his poke-and-farm playstyle.","At 3 your Double Up combo beats him straight-up with no self-peel on his side.","Through levels 4-5 his zero mobility lets you walk him down on Wall of Pain cooldowns.","At 6 Requiem's global execute evens the phase - low-HP misplays let his ult punish you.","At one item your Bullet Time burst re-establishes the edge on a squishy caster.","By two-plus items you still out-duel his defenseless frame up close."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"kogmaw","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Kog'Maw"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"With Q Double Up and E Make It Rain rank-up you out-range and out-poke Kog'Maw, whose W is off before it comes online; every time he steps up to last-hit you drop E on the wave and weave autos to shove him off the CS and under tower."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is a fight-ender on an immobile champion — hold it for when your support lands CC or when Kog W-kites into your minions, and he has no dash to break the channel; you win almost every 2v2 all-in through 6 as long as you respect his jungler."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike on a lethality or crit rush lands before Kog's W ramps to relevance, so keep punishing his short range and deny him free farm — a Kog who reaches items even is already ahead of the curve."},{"when":"Late","text":"This is where the matchup flips: Kog'Maw with W plus attack speed and Guinsoo shreds you from a range your Bullet Time can't safely close, so in 5v5 you must one-shot him with ult behind a peel or never commit face-to-face."}],"wants":{"you":["End the game before Kog'Maw completes two attack-speed items","Punish his short auto range every time he steps to CS","Save Bullet Time for his fixed position or when support CCs"],"foe":["Farm safely under tower and reach W plus Guinsoo online","Have his support peel and zone you off his back line","Kite in a straight line so your ult and closing autos whiff"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 you have the stronger base auto and Q harass while Kog'Maw is a farming turret with no W power spike yet — trade autos when he goes for a minion and use E to slow him if he tries to walk you down.","mid":"From 3 through 6 you dominate: E controls the wave and his approach, Q Double Up bounces punish him behind minions, and level 6 Bullet Time locks a champion who has zero mobility to dodge the channel, so look to all-in on his mistakes with support CC.","late":"Once Kog'Maw finishes his attack-speed and shred items he out-DPS's and out-ranges you, so the game becomes a race — snowball your first-item lead into objectives, and in teamfights only ult him from an angle where his frontline can't punish your position.","whys":["Level 1 you hold the stronger base auto and Q harass against a Kog'Maw who is purely farming.","Level 2 your early rank in Make It Rain and Double Up out-trades his short-range last-hitting.","Level 3 E slow plus Q poke lets you shove and deny CS before his W matters.","Levels 4-5 you out-range and out-poke him while his scaling W is still off.","Level 6 Bullet Time is a guaranteed hit on an immobile Kog'Maw for a winning all-in.","Your first-item spike arrives before Kog's attack-speed ramp makes him dangerous.","At 2+ items Kog'Maw's W shred and range out-scale you, flipping the lane to him."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"lucian","win":["Lucian","Lucian","Lucian","Lucian","Skill","Lucian","Lucian"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Lucian owns this window: his Passive Lightslinger double-shot, Q Piercing Light through minions, and E Relentless Pursuit dash let him burst-trade and reposition faster than your static autos, so you cannot win an extended stand-up fight and must play for CS behind the wave."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"At 6 it evens out — your Bullet Time can punish a Lucian who dashes in without E up, but a good Lucian holds E to break the channel, so treat level 6 as a skill check on catching him mid-dash or with your support's CC."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Lucian's first-item spike on an Essence Reaver or crit rush amplifies his burst combo and E cooldown reset on hits, so he re-enters trades faster than you can kite out; respect his dash timers and only fight when E is on cooldown."},{"when":"Late","text":"Even into items Lucian's mobility lets him dodge your Bullet Time and disengage your Q, but your value shifts to teamfights — position on the flank and fire ult across his whole team while your frontline denies his dash angles."}],"wants":{"you":["Farm safely and avoid extended trades while his E is up","Catch him after he burns Relentless Pursuit dash","Reach teamfights where Bullet Time hits multiple targets"],"foe":["Land Passive double-shots and Q poke in short trades","Use E to dodge your ult and re-engage repeatedly","Snowball his lane lead before your teamfight scaling matters"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 Lucian already out-trades you: his Lightslinger passive turns every ability into a double hit and his Q pokes you through the minion line while your kit has no dash to answer, so give ground and focus on last-hitting.","mid":"From 3 through 6 Lucian's dash-heavy burst pattern beats your immobile trading — hold E respect, farm under tower, and only look for a fight at 6 when he has dashed in or your support lands hard CC to let Bullet Time channel safely.","late":"With items Lucian stays slippery and can peel your ult with E, but Miss Fortune's overall scaling and AoE teamfight ult carry games — space on the side, fire Bullet Time into a clustered enemy, and let your team wall off his re-dash.","whys":["Level 1 Lucian's Lightslinger double-shots out-trade your single autos.","Level 2 his Q poke and burst combo dominate the short trading window.","Level 3 E Relentless Pursuit gives him repositioning you cannot match.","Levels 4-5 his mobility and burst keep you pinned off even trades.","Level 6 is a skill check — your ult can punish him only if he mistimes E.","At first item Lucian's burst and dash resets re-engage faster than you kite.","At 2+ items his mobility still dodges your ult, keeping the lane his."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"nilah","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Nilah","Nilah"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Nilah is a melee ADC, so early you abuse range hard: E Make It Rain zones her off the wave, Q Double Up and autos poke her every time she walks up to whip a minion, and you shove so she takes tower CS while eating harass."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Level 6 is even — your Bullet Time is huge damage but Nilah's W Jaws of the Beast gives her a dodge/lifesteal window and her ult Apotheosis pulls enemies in for a lifesteal-fueled all-in, so it becomes a timing and support-CC duel."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Nilah spikes hard on her first item because her lifesteal-sharing and W dodge let her stat-check you once she closes range; if she gets on top of you with items she out-sustains your poke, so keep her out and never fight in melee."},{"when":"Late","text":"With items and her vacuum ult Nilah is a lane and skirmish threat, but in 5v5 you still fire Bullet Time from max range behind your frontline — the moment she dives your backline is the moment your team collapses on her."}],"wants":{"you":["Poke Nilah with E and Q while she's stuck at melee range","Shove the wave so she can't safely last-hit","End skirmishes before her lifesteal and W dodge come online"],"foe":["Close the gap and stat-check you with lifesteal sharing","Use W to dodge your key autos then all-in with ult","Reach items where her sustain out-values your poke"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 your range is a free advantage over a melee Nilah — auto and Q her whenever she steps to CS, and drop E to slow her approach so she bleeds health just trying to farm.","mid":"From 3 through 5 you keep out-ranging and poking her off the wave, but at 6 it evens out: her W dodge and Apotheosis lifesteal all-in can flip a fight, so only commit Bullet Time with your support's CC landed and her W on cooldown.","late":"Once Nilah completes her first item her lifesteal and dodge let her out-trade you in melee, so the lane tilts to her — respect her engage, and in teamfights space wide and ult across her whole team while your frontline peels her off you.","whys":["Level 1 your ranged autos punish a melee Nilah who must walk into you to farm.","Level 2 E and Q let you poke and zone her off the wave freely.","Level 3 your range and Make It Rain slow keep her from safe last-hits.","Levels 4-5 you continue to out-poke her while she has no ranged answer.","Level 6 is even — her W dodge and lifesteal ult trade evenly with your Bullet Time.","At first item Nilah's lifesteal and dodge let her out-sustain your poke.","At 2+ items her sustain and vacuum ult out-value you in extended fights."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"samira","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Samira","Samira","Samira","Samira"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"By 3 it's even and by 4-5 Samira takes over: her E Wild Rush dash-to-target and W Blade Whirl that destroys your projectiles neutralize your poke, and once she gets adjacent she stacks her Style meter and burst-trades you off the wave."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Samira's Inferno Trigger ult at full Style is a game-ending AoE spin, and unlike your channeled Bullet Time she can W away incoming CC and Q-cancel; if she flashes or E's onto you at S-rank you lose the 2v2 unless your support hard-locks her first."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Samira snowballs brutally on her first item — lifesteal plus attack speed feeds her Style engine and healing, so a fed Samira dives your backline and heals through your damage; keep her off you and never let her free-cast W into your autos."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game Samira is one of the scariest divers and her W eats your Bullet Time projectiles at the worst moment, so in teamfights fire ult only when she has committed her dash and W elsewhere, and rely on your team to chain-CC her mid-combo."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish Samira hard at levels 1-2 before she comes online","Poke her down before she can safely E onto the wave","Fight only when her W Blade Whirl is on cooldown"],"foe":["Reach level 3+ and stack Style for burst trades","Use W to destroy your poke and E to close instantly","Snowball a first-item lifesteal spike into backline dives"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are your window: Samira wants melee range and has no dash yet, so auto and Q her aggressively when she steps up, and use E to slow her so she can't safely last-hit or engage.","mid":"By level 3 it's a coin-flip and from 4 onward Samira wins — her Wild Rush dash and W projectile-wipe blank your poke, she stacks Style for burst, and at 6 her Inferno Trigger out-duels your Bullet Time, so play safe and never fight into her W.","late":"With a lifesteal first item Samira snowballs and out-sustains your damage while diving, so the lane and skirmishes favor her — in 5v5 hold Bullet Time until she has burned W and E, and let your team lock her the instant she jumps in.","whys":["Level 1 your range punishes a dashless melee Samira before she spikes.","Level 2 you can still poke and zone her off CS with autos and E.","Level 3 it evens out as her kit and Style meter come online.","Levels 4-5 her Wild Rush and W projectile-wipe overtake your poke.","Level 6 Inferno Trigger out-duels your channeled Bullet Time all-in.","At first item her lifesteal spike lets her dive and heal through you.","At 2+ items Samira's diving and W-timing keep the matchup hers."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"senna","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Senna"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Senna's base attack speed is miserable and she leans on soul stacking, so you out-DPS her outright — punish every last-hit with Q and autos, and drop E to zone her off the wave so she can't safely collect Mist souls or CS."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time massively out-damages Senna's Dawning Shadow ult in a 2v2, and she has no dash to escape the channel; hold it for when your support lands CC and you can end the all-in before her long-range Q pokes you down."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike lands while Senna is still an early-game DPS liability, so keep denying her souls and freezing her out of farm — every soul you starve is range and AD she never gets."},{"when":"Late","text":"This is where Senna flips: stacked souls give her huge range, crit, and lifesteal, and her global ult shields her team while she pokes from a distance your Bullet Time can't reach, so late teamfights favor her scaling if you let her stack freely."}],"wants":{"you":["Punish Senna's weak base attack speed in every trade","Deny her souls and starve her scaling early","End the game before her stacks make her a hypercarry"],"foe":["Free-stack Mist souls to snowball range and AD","Poke you down from long range with empowered Q","Reach late game where her scaling out-ranges your ult"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 you have far better base damage and attack speed than a Senna who's built around stacking, so auto-trade her aggressively when she steps to last-hit and use E to slow her off the wave.","mid":"From 3 through 6 you dominate: Q and E control the wave and her approach, her low attack speed means she loses every stand-up trade, and Bullet Time out-damages her ult in an all-in, so look to punish and deny her souls whenever she overextends.","late":"Once Senna stacks enough Mist she gains oppressive range, crit, and lifesteal and can poke you from outside your ult's reach, so the game tilts to her — close it out early, and in 5v5 dive her before she kites, using your ult when her Dawning Shadow is down.","whys":["Level 1 your base damage and attack speed crush a stacking-reliant Senna.","Level 2 you out-trade her weak early autos and zone her with E.","Level 3 Q and E let you shove and deny her soul collection.","Levels 4-5 your DPS keeps her starved off farm and souls.","Level 6 Bullet Time out-damages her ult with no escape for her.","Your first-item spike arrives while Senna is still an early-game liability.","At 2+ items Senna's stacked range and crit out-scale you into her favor."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"seraphine","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Seraphine"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"You out-DPS Seraphine in any stand-up trade — she's an immobile caster who relies on Q High Note poke and E Beat Drop, so weave through minions to dodge her skillshots, punish with Q and autos, and shove her under tower where her mana runs dry."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time hard out-damages Seraphine in a 2v2 and she has no dash to leave the channel; the only threat is her E root chaining into her ult Encore, so all-in when her E is on cooldown or your support can force her to blow it early."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike keeps you ahead — a lethality or crit rush lets you dive an immobile Seraphine before her poke adds up, so keep punishing her mana and range while she's still squishy and slow."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game flips: Seraphine's stacked Q, team-wide W shields/heals, and a massive Encore that can chain-charm your whole team let her control fights from range, so respect her ult and fire Bullet Time only after her E and R are spent."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge her Q and E through minions then punish with autos","All-in her immobile kit when E Beat Drop is down","Snowball your item lead before her utility scales"],"foe":["Poke you with High Note and root you with Beat Drop","Land a multi-target Encore charm in teamfights","Reach late game where her shields and CC control fights"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 you have stronger base damage than a poke-reliant Seraphine and she has no mobility, so trade autos when she steps up and use E to slow her so her skillshots are easier to walk out of.","mid":"From 3 onward you mostly win the lane — you out-DPS her, dodge her Q and E behind minions, and at 6 Bullet Time out-damages her all-in; the one even window is 4-5 when her poke and E root can punish a bad step, so play clean around her cooldowns.","late":"With items Seraphine's amplified poke, W shields, and chain-charm Encore let her dictate teamfights from safety, so the game tilts to her utility — close it out early, and in 5v5 hold your ult until her E and R are down, then delete her from max range.","whys":["Level 1 your base damage beats a poke-reliant, immobile Seraphine.","Level 2 you out-trade her autos and can dodge her early skillshots.","Level 3 you out-DPS her and shove her low on mana under tower.","Levels 4-5 it evens out as her Q poke and E root can punish missteps.","Level 6 Bullet Time out-damages her all-in with no escape for her.","Your first-item spike lets you dive her immobile kit before her poke adds up.","At 2+ items her shields, poke, and chain-charm ult out-scale you in fights."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"sivir","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Sivir"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"With Double Up and Strut you out-trade Sivir hard through the early levels; her Boomerang Blade (Q) chunks minions but does little to you if you stand behind your caster wave, and her low base AD means she can't punish your last-hits under tower the way you punish hers."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is a real all-in threat if you can get Sivir pinned, but her Spell Shield (E) can eat your engage CC and On The Hunt (R) lets her whole team disengage your channel, so the level-6 window is skill-dependent on baiting the shield first."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike (Kraken or Galeforce into Berserker's) keeps you ahead in raw DPS trades since Sivir has no self-peel besides the shield and folds to a supported all-in once E is down."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game tilts to Sivir: her R team-wide movement speed and shield-per-hit sustain let her kite your Bullet Time and reposition the fight, so her utility out-scales your static AoE damage in 5v5s."}],"wants":{"you":["Bait out Sivir's Spell Shield with an ability or minion damage before committing your all-in","Stand behind your minions so her Boomerang Blade and Ricochet don't zone your CS","Punish her short push cadence by trading every time her Q is on cooldown"],"foe":["Hold Spell Shield to negate your engage or your support's key CC","Use On The Hunt to kite your Bullet Time channel and disengage sieges","Farm safely to two items where her R utility carries teamfights"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 favour you: Double Up threatens the kill pattern Sivir can't match and her weak early damage means you win every even trade and control the wave for tower CS.","mid":"Through 3-5 you stay ahead with Strut sustain and superior burst, but level 6 becomes skill-based because her Spell Shield and On The Hunt can nullify your ult if you mistime it.","late":"After first item you hold the DPS edge, but by two items Sivir's R and shield-sustain out-scale your static AoE, so close the game before her utility takes over.","whys":["You win level 1 because Double Up plus Strut gives a kill pattern Sivir's weak early kit can't answer.","Level 2 stays yours as your two-point trade damage outpaces her Boomerang poke.","At level 3 your all-in threat with support CC beats her when her shield is down.","Levels 4-5 remain yours on Strut sustain and superior last-hit safety.","Level 6 is skill because Bullet Time can be shielded or kited by On The Hunt if you misread her cooldowns.","First item is skill as your DPS spike meets her shield-per-hit sustain evenly in extended trades.","At two items Sivir wins: her R movement speed and shield out-scale your static AoE damage in fights."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"smolder","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Smolder"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"This is your kingdom: Smolder is a scaling stacker who is nearly harmless early, so hammer him with Double Up and auto-Strut trades every time he steps up to last-hit and deny his Super Scorcher Breath (Q) stacks by zoning him off CS."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is a hard punish here because Smolder has no dash or self-peel at 6 beyond flimsy Achooo! (W) poke; land the channel behind minions with support CC and you can end the lane before he ever comes online."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item power spike lands far sooner than his stack threshold, so keep denying him and look to snowball plates and kills while he is still weak and stack-starved."},{"when":"Late","text":"Once Smolder crosses 125 stacks his Q becomes a long-range execute nuke and his R gives disengage and burst, so late game hard-favours him unless you closed the game during his weak phase."}],"wants":{"you":["Deny Smolder's Q stacks by zoning him off every wave in the first ten minutes","All-in repeatedly through levels 3-6 while he has no escape","Convert your lead into towers and dragons before he hits his stack breakpoints"],"foe":["Farm safely and stack Q to 125 for the long-range execute","Use W poke and R disengage to survive your all-in windows","Scale to two-plus items where his ranged burst out-duels you"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are yours outright: Smolder is a pure scaler with no early damage, so you control the wave and threaten him off his opening stacks with Double Up.","mid":"Through 3-6 you dominate every trade and every all-in because he has no dash and minimal self-peel, making this the window to snowball hard.","late":"After first item you still hold the edge, but once his Q stacks mature past two items Smolder's execute and R out-scale you, so end early.","whys":["You win level 1 as Smolder has zero early damage and you own the trade with Double Up.","Level 2 stays yours since your two-point burst crushes his stack-starved kit.","Level 3 favours you because your supported all-in beats his no-escape early laning.","Levels 4-5 remain yours as he still lacks a dash to survive your Strut trades.","Level 6 is yours: Bullet Time punishes his immobility before he comes online.","First item stays yours because your spike arrives long before his 125-stack threshold.","At two items Smolder wins: his stacked Q execute and R burst out-scale your kit late."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"swain","win":["Miss Fortune","Skill","Skill","Swain","Swain","Skill","Skill"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Swain is a bot-lane pick played for the Nevermove (W) root and Vision of Empire (E) pull, and once he hits three points his poke-and-pull kit starts to outrange your Double Up trades; respect the E from fog and never stand in a straight line with your support when his root is up."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Demonic Ascension flips extended fights hard: if Swain lands E-W and drops his R on top of you and your support, his drain-tank healing out-sustains your Bullet Time chip, so his level-6 all-in threat clearly outpaces yours in a 2v2."},{"when":"1st item","text":"On completing his first item Swain's sustain and E cooldown come down enough that his threat evens out with yours, so play the CS game and only commit when his E is on cooldown."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game normalizes to skill: in teamfights your Bullet Time and his R AoE both want the same clumped fight, and it comes down to who lands their AoE and CC first from good positioning."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge Vision of Empire from fog and never line up with your support for his root","Trade only when his E is on cooldown and punish his mediocre wave clear","Poke him below drain-tank threshold before he can R-heal back to full"],"foe":["Land E into W root to lock you for a support all-in","Bait your Bullet Time then Demonic Ascension to out-sustain the trade","Drag fights long where his R healing beats your burst"]},"early":"Level 1 is yours because Swain has no meaningful one-point damage and you win the raw Double Up trade before his kit comes online.","mid":"From level 2 it turns skill-based and then to Swain at 4-6: his E-W pull combo and Demonic Ascension out-threaten you in extended 2v2s, so trade on his cooldowns rather than brawling.","late":"After first item the lane evens back to skill; both of you fight for the same clumped teamfight and it hinges on who lands AoE and CC first.","whys":["You win level 1 as Swain lacks early trade damage and loses the straight Double Up exchange.","Level 2 is skill because his W root threat begins to offset your poke edge.","Level 3 stays skill as his E poke and your trades cancel out on cooldowns.","Levels 4-5 favour Swain: his E-W pull sets up a winning supported all-in on you.","Level 6 is Swain's because Demonic Ascension out-sustains your Bullet Time in a brawl.","First item is skill as his sustain meets your DPS spike evenly.","At two items it stays skill: both ults want the same clumped fight and positioning decides it."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"tristana","win":["Miss Fortune","Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Skill","Tristana"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once Tristana has Rocket Jump (W) and Explosive Charge (E) the lane is a spacing duel; she can leap onto you to detonate her E stacks, but that burns her only escape, so bait the W and punish her landing with Double Up and a Strut-empowered auto before she can reset it on a kill or takedown."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Buster Shot is a get-off-me and disengage tool that can knock you out of your own Bullet Time, so the level-6 window is even; your channel wins only if you fire it after she has already spent W and R, otherwise she resets the trade."},{"when":"1st item","text":"First item stays a skill matchup: her E-detonation burst spikes with attack speed while your Double Up and item power keep trades even, so it comes down to who respects the other's all-in range."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game favours Tristana: her passive attack range grows every level and her W-R reset pattern gives her safe repositioning your immobile Bullet Time lacks, so she out-duels and out-scales you into two-plus items."}],"wants":{"you":["Bait Rocket Jump then punish her landing while her escape is down","Space so her Explosive Charge stacks fall off before they detonate","Fight before level 13-16 when her range passive out-zones you"],"foe":["Use W to gap-close, detonate E, and W-reset off the kill","Save Buster Shot to knock you out of Bullet Time","Scale to late game where her range and resets out-duel you"]},"early":"Level 1 is yours because you out-damage a low-level Tristana in a straight trade before she has Rocket Jump to threaten a reset.","mid":"From 2 through 6 it is a skill spacing duel: her W-E burst and Buster Shot disengage trade evenly with your Double Up as long as you respect her all-in range.","late":"After first item it stays skill, but by two items Tristana's growing range and W-R resets out-scale your immobile kit, so pressure her early.","whys":["You win level 1 as Tristana's early damage is low and you take the clean Double Up trade.","Level 2 is skill once Rocket Jump gives her a reset-and-escape you must play around.","Level 3 stays skill as her E burst and your poke cancel out on cooldowns.","Levels 4-5 remain skill in the spacing duel around her W escape.","Level 6 is skill because Buster Shot can cancel your Bullet Time and reset the trade.","First item is skill as her attack-speed burst meets your item spike evenly.","At two items Tristana wins: her range passive and W-R resets out-duel and out-scale you late."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"twitch","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Twitch"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Twitch is a scaling stealth carry who is desperately weak in a straight 2v2, so bully him: Double Up plus Strut wins every trade, and his Ambush (Q) stealth is only good for roaming or repositioning, not for beating you in a stand-up fight over CS."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is a lane-ending threat because Twitch has no dash and squishy stats; if he ever channels Spray and Pray to fight you head-on before he has items, your ult plus support CC deletes him first."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first-item spike lands well before Twitch's, so keep denying and warding his stealth flanks; a pink ward on his approach lines removes the one tool that lets him escape your lane dominance."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game hard-favours Twitch: once he has crit items his Contaminate (E) plus Spray and Pray shreds your whole team through minions, and his range on R can out-DPS your Bullet Time in a clumped fight, so close the game before he online."}],"wants":{"you":["Bully Twitch in every straight trade before he has items","Ward his stealth flank lines with pinks to deny repositioning","Snowball towers and dragons before his crit spike arrives"],"foe":["Use Ambush stealth to roam or reposition rather than duel you","Farm safely to crit items for his Spray and Pray teamfight spike","Contaminate stacks through minions in a clumped late fight"]},"early":"Levels 1-2 are yours: Twitch has no early trading power, so your Double Up controls the wave and threatens him off CS constantly.","mid":"Through 3-6 you dominate every duel and every all-in because his immobile squishy kit folds to your Strut trades and Bullet Time.","late":"After first item you keep the edge, but by two-plus crit items Twitch's Spray and Pray shred out-scales your kit, so end the game early.","whys":["You win level 1 as Twitch has no early damage and loses every straight trade.","Level 2 stays yours since your two-point burst crushes his weak laning.","Level 3 favours you because your supported all-in punishes his immobility.","Levels 4-5 remain yours as his stealth can't win a stand-up Strut trade.","Level 6 is yours: Bullet Time deletes his squishy no-dash frame with support CC.","First item stays yours because your spike lands long before his crit power comes online.","At two items Twitch wins: crit Spray and Pray plus Contaminate shred out-scale your AoE."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"varus","win":["Skill","Skill","Skill","Varus","Skill","Varus","Varus"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Varus poke builds around Piercing Arrow (Q) charge and Blighted Quiver (W) stacks, and once he can detonate three blight stacks with a charged Q his lane poke out-ranges your Double Up trades; hide behind minions to break his Q line and don't let him free-stack W on you at the wave."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"The level-6 window is even because Chain of Corruption is a long-range engage that can start a fight, but it is also a single-target root your support can body-block, so if you sidestep or eat his R with a tanky ally your Bullet Time answers his engage cleanly."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Varus spikes hard on his first item since attack-speed or lethality both accelerate his blight-detonation poke, so his sustained ranged damage edges ahead of yours during the siege phase; play safe and farm rather than face-checking his Q."},{"when":"Late","text":"Late game favours Varus's poke pattern: his R engage plus stacked blight melts you before you can channel, and his range lets him kite your immobile Bullet Time, though your teamfight AoE keeps games winnable if your team punishes his committed R."}],"wants":{"you":["Break his Piercing Arrow line by standing behind minions","Deny free Blighted Quiver stacks at the wave","Have your support body-block or sidestep his Chain of Corruption engage"],"foe":["Charge Q into three blight stacks for max poke","Open fights with a long-range Chain of Corruption root","Spike on first item and kite your immobile Bullet Time"]},"early":"Levels 1-3 are a skill poke duel: Varus's charged Q out-ranges you but his early blight stacks are slow to build, so deny them and the lane stays even.","mid":"From level 4 Varus edges ahead on blight-detonation poke, though level 6 is even because his R engage can be body-blocked; respect his range and farm the siege.","late":"After first item Varus's poke spike and R engage out-scale you, so lean on your teamfight AoE and punish his committed ult rather than dueling him head-on.","whys":["Level 1 is skill as his Q range and your trade damage roughly cancel out.","Level 2 stays skill while his blight stacks are still too slow to punish you.","Level 3 remains skill as your Double Up matches his early charged-Q poke.","Levels 4-5 favour Varus once three-stack blight detonations out-poke your trades.","Level 6 is skill because his R engage is strong but single-target and body-blockable.","First item is Varus's: attack-speed or lethality accelerates his blight poke past yours.","At two items Varus wins: R engage plus stacked blight melt and kite your immobile ult."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"vayne","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Vayne"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Once you have Double Up (Q) plus Strut and a rank in Make it Rain (E), you out-range and out-DPS Vayne every second she's on the map. She has no waveclear and a 550-range auto with no poke, so shove the wave, freeze her out of XP, and punch her every time she steps up to last-hit under threat of a Q bounce off the caster minion."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time is a massive 2v2 win button here: Vayne's only escape is Tumble (Q) and a short Condemn (E) stun, neither of which cancels your channel. If your support lands any CC, fire your ult from behind minions and you delete her before Final Hour ever matters. Respect that a good Vayne saves Condemn to peel your engage, not to trade."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your Galeforce or Kraken/Essence Reaver spike lands well before Vayne comes online, since she needs three items and Final Hour to threaten you. Keep sidestepping so she can't stack Silver Bolts, and use your first-item burst to end lane before her scaling arrives."},{"when":"Late","text":"This is where it flips. With Final Hour up, Vayne's invisibility, movespeed, and true-damage Silver Bolts shred you in extended fights, and Condemn can pin you to walls. Play grouped, never get caught alone, and use Bullet Time from max range so you're not in her Tumble-reset kill window."}],"wants":{"you":["Shove waves and deny her CS and XP while she has no clear","Bait Tumble/Condemn cooldowns before you commit your all-in","Force fights before she finishes her second and third items"],"foe":["Farm safely to three items and Final Hour to spike","Save Condemn to peel your engage instead of trading","Drag the game to teamfights where invisibility and true damage carry"]},"early":"You win level 1-2 outright: Double Up out-ranges her 550 auto and she has zero poke or waveclear, so poke her off every last hit and set up a shove.","mid":"From 3 to 6 you dominate every trade window on her cooldowns, and Bullet Time plus any support CC is a clean 2v2 kill button before Vayne has items.","late":"After first item you're still ahead, but with two-plus items and Final Hour Vayne out-scales you hard, so close the game early and never fight her alone.","whys":["You win level 1 because Double Up out-ranges Vayne's short auto and she has no poke to contest it.","At level 2 your extra Strut and Q pressure let you punish every step-up while she still can't waveclear.","Level 3 favours you as full Q-E-Strut out-trades her before Silver Bolts scaling exists.","Through levels 4-5 you keep the range and DPS edge while she has no items to threaten back.","At 6 Bullet Time plus support CC is an all-in Vayne can't cancel with Tumble or Condemn.","At first item your Galeforce spike lands before Vayne's three-item power comes online.","With two-plus items Final Hour's invisibility, movespeed, and true damage let Vayne out-scale and shred you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"veigar","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Veigar bot is a control mage with no sustained DPS and a slow, telegraphed Baleful Strike (Q) that you sidestep behind minions. With Double Up and Make it Rain you out-DPS and out-range him constantly, so shove hard, dodge his Q, and force him to burn mana on waveclear he doesn't have."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time out-damages his combo in a straight fight, but his real threat is Event Horizon (E) cage. Fire your ult from range only once his cage is down or you're behind minions, and Strut through his Dark Matter (W) landing zone. With support CC you can all-in before his stun is back up."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your first crit item spike arrives before Veigar assembles the AP and stacks he needs to one-shot you. Keep spacing so his Q can only hit you through the minion wave, and punish him whenever Event Horizon is on cooldown."},{"when":"Late","text":"Veigar scales infinitely with Q stacks, so late Event Horizon into Dark Matter into R is a genuine 100-to-0. Never walk into his cage range, hold Flash for his stun, and use Bullet Time from max range so you deal damage without eating his combo."}],"wants":{"you":["Sidestep Baleful Strike and punish his lack of waveclear","Shove and deny his stacks by making him miss last hits","Force fights while his Event Horizon and Flash are down"],"foe":["Land Q on you through minions to farm stacks and poke","Catch you in Event Horizon to chain Dark Matter and ult","Reach enough AP and stacks to one-shot you from the cage"]},"early":"You out-range and out-DPS Veigar from level 1: Double Up pokes freely while his only tool is a slow Baleful Strike you dodge behind the wave.","mid":"Through 3-6 you keep the trade and shove advantage; just respect Event Horizon and only commit Bullet Time when his cage or your Flash makes the all-in safe.","late":"Even with items you stay ahead of a mage with no DPS, but never step into cage range where stacked Dark Matter plus R can burst you.","whys":["You win level 1 as Double Up out-ranges and out-DPSs a control mage with only a slow, dodgeable Q.","At level 2 your added damage and Strut punish his complete lack of early waveclear.","Level 3 favours you because full Q-E out-trades him and he can't stack safely under pressure.","Through 4-5 you keep shoving and poking while his stun-reliant kit can't answer your DPS.","At 6 Bullet Time plus support CC out-damages his combo before his AP and stacks come online.","At first item your crit spike lands before Veigar has the AP to one-shot you.","With two-plus items you still win by respecting cage range, denying the all-in that would otherwise threaten you."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"xayah","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Skill","Skill","Skill","Xayah"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Early you out-poke Xayah: Double Up hits harder than her Double Daggers (Q) and she has to walk into feather range to trade, exposing herself to Make it Rain slow. Shove and punish her before she has enough feathers on the ground to threaten a Bladecaller (E) root. The lane goes even by 4-5 as her feather zoning and lifesteal come online."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"This is skill-dependent: Bullet Time and Featherstorm (R) trade blows, but her R is a clean channel-and-untargetable dodge that dodges your ult and sets up her own root. Only commit Bullet Time when her R is down; if she ults into your channel, you waste it. With support CC first, you still win the all-in."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Roughly even at one item. Both of you spike on crit, but Xayah's Bladecaller root plus Featherstorm gives her the safer all-in pattern in a 2v2, so respect her feather count and don't over-extend into a full root setup."},{"when":"Late","text":"Xayah pulls ahead late: her Featherstorm is a get-out-of-jail dodge and a teamfight root that punishes your immobile channel, and her feather zoning controls the fight. Position on the flank, fire Bullet Time only after her R is spent, and never facecheck into a feather-loaded lane."}],"wants":{"you":["Poke with Double Up before she builds feathers on the ground","Shove and punish her early when her E root has no ammo","Bait Featherstorm before committing Bullet Time"],"foe":["Stack feathers and land Bladecaller roots to set up her all-in","Use Featherstorm to dodge your ult and untarget your engage","Reach late-game where her R controls the teamfight"]},"early":"You win the first three levels: Double Up out-pokes her Double Daggers and she must enter your range to fight, eating Make it Rain.","mid":"By 4-6 it evens to a skill matchup - her feather zoning, lifesteal, and Featherstorm answer your poke, so only ult when her R is down.","late":"With items Xayah edges ahead because Featherstorm dodges your channel and roots the fight, so play the flank and respect her feathers.","whys":["You win level 1 because Double Up out-pokes Double Daggers and she must step into your range to trade.","At level 2 your damage still leads before she has feathers on the ground to threaten a root.","Level 3 favours you as full Q-E out-trades her while her Bladecaller ammo is thin.","By levels 4-5 it's even - her feather zoning and lifesteal now match your poke.","At 6 it's skill: Featherstorm can dodge your Bullet Time, so the all-in hinges on cooldown timing.","At first item both spike on crit, leaving the trade roughly even.","With two-plus items Xayah's Featherstorm dodge and teamfight root punish your immobile ult and pull her ahead."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"zeri","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Zeri"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Zeri is one of the weakest early ADCs and you punish it: her Burst Fire (Q) does little without items, and her auto-charged W poke is easy to dodge behind minions. With Double Up and Make it Rain you out-DPS and out-trade her hard, so shove the wave, deny CS, and force her off the wave every time she steps up. Her passive shield is her only defense and you break it fast."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time massively out-damages a level-6 Zeri who has no burst yet, and her ult Lightning Crash gives her energized attacks but no escape. If you ult from behind minions with support CC, she has only her E dash over a wall to survive. This is a prime all-in window before she scales."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Careful: Zeri's power is entirely items. Once she completes her first crit/on-hit item her Q starts shredding and her mobility spikes, so cash in your lead in the first 15 minutes rather than letting her farm to her item breakpoints."},{"when":"Late","text":"Zeri hard out-scales you: her E dash resets, constant movespeed, and Lightning Crash energized autos make her nearly impossible to pin down while you're a stationary Bullet Time channel. Fire your ult from max range on the flank, rely on support CC to catch her, and never fight her in an open area where she kites you forever."}],"wants":{"you":["Shove and punish her feeble early laning phase","All-in at 6 before her item breakpoints arrive","End the game before her first two items come online"],"foe":["Farm safely to her crit/on-hit item spikes","Use E dash resets and movespeed to kite your ult","Scale to late game where energized autos out-DPS you"]},"early":"You crush the early game: Zeri's item-dependent kit does almost no damage at levels 1-3, so out-DPS her, break her shield, and deny CS.","mid":"Through 4-6 you keep the trade edge, and Bullet Time plus support CC is a clean all-in before her scaling kicks in.","late":"After her first items Zeri out-scales you hard with dash resets and energized autos, so close early and only ult her from the flank at max range.","whys":["You win level 1 because Zeri's item-reliant Q and W do almost nothing while Double Up out-DPSs her.","At level 2 your damage and shield-break punish her feeble early laning.","Level 3 favours you as full combo out-trades a champion with no early power.","Through 4-5 you keep denying CS while she has no item breakpoints reached.","At 6 Bullet Time out-damages a burst-less Zeri and support CC seals the all-in.","At first item your crit spike still leads, but this is the last window before she scales.","With two-plus items Zeri's dash resets, movespeed, and energized autos let her kite and out-DPS your channel."]},
  {"a":"missfortune_bot","b":"ziggs","win":["Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune","Miss Fortune"],"spikes":[{"when":"Lvl 3-5","text":"Ziggs bot is a poke mage with no reliable escape and a slow Bouncing Bomb (Q) you dodge behind minions. With Double Up and Make it Rain you out-DPS him in any straight fight, so weave through his Q, force him to waste mana, and shove so he can't freely lob bombs. His Satchel Charge (W) is his only disengage, so bait it before you commit."},{"when":"Lvl 6","text":"Bullet Time out-trades his combo, and his ult Mega Inferno Bomb is a long-range execute-poke, not a self-peel. His only escape from your all-in is one Satchel Charge knockback. If you engage from behind minions with support CC, you kill him before Minefield (E) or W can save him."},{"when":"1st item","text":"Your crit spike lands and lets you all-in through his poke; he has no DPS and no mobility to answer you. Respect his Minefield zoning around objectives, but in a straight 2v2 your item power beats his."},{"when":"Late","text":"Even late you stay ahead of an immobile artillery mage: Ziggs pokes but can't survive your dive. Watch for Satchel Charge to knock you out of Bullet Time, use Minefield-free angles, and flank so his slow bombs can't zone you before you close the gap."}],"wants":{"you":["Dodge Bouncing Bomb behind minions and out-DPS him","Bait Satchel Charge before committing your all-in","Dive him with support CC where he has no escape"],"foe":["Poke you down with Q and Mega Inferno Bomb from range","Use Satchel Charge to knock you out of Bullet Time","Zone objectives with Minefield to avoid a straight fight"]},"early":"You win early: Double Up out-DPSs a poke mage whose only tools are a slow, dodgeable Q and a single Satchel disengage.","mid":"Through 3-6 you keep the DPS and shove edge, and Bullet Time plus support CC kills him through his lone Satchel escape.","late":"Even with items you beat an immobile artillery mage - just respect Satchel knockback on your ult and flank past his Minefield zoning.","whys":["You win level 1 as Double Up out-DPSs a mage armed only with a slow, dodgeable Bouncing Bomb.","At level 2 your damage punishes his lack of any early self-peel beyond one Satchel.","Level 3 favours you because full combo out-trades a poke mage with no DPS.","Through 4-5 you keep shoving and diving while he can't answer your sustained damage.","At 6 Bullet Time out-trades his combo and support CC beats his single Satchel escape.","At first item your crit spike lets you all-in through his poke unanswered.","With two-plus items you still beat an immobile artillery mage by respecting Satchel and flanking his Minefield."]}
